        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to fill an ITC-04 form?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Form ITC-04 is filed on the GST portal by the principal manufacturer, listing goods sent to each job worker and goods received back, with challan number, date, description, quantity and taxable value. The details are picked up from the delivery challan issued under Rule 55 of the CGST Rules, because job work movement goes out on a challan and not a tax invoice."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between a job work delivery challan and Form ITC-04?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A delivery challan under Rule 55 accompanies each consignment sent to a job worker, while Form ITC-04 is the periodic summary of all such challans issued and goods received back. The challan is a transport document, whereas ITC-04 is the compliance filing that lets the principal prove inputs were returned inside the time limit set by Section 143."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What happens if job work goods are not returned within the time limit?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "If inputs are not received back within one year and capital goods within three years, Section 143 of the CGST Act treats the original despatch as a supply made on the day the goods were sent out. The principal then pays GST with interest from that date, which is why ITC-04 tracking matters for the time limit and not only for filing."
          }
        }
      ]
